  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Photos sell an impression. Plans sell a decision. When a buyer moves from mild interest to serious consideration, the first thing they do is study the floor plan. They are assessing flow, how rooms connect, what is adjacent to what, room dimensions, aspect, and renovation potential. Photos alone cannot answer those questions, and buyers who cannot answer them tend to walk away.</p>

      <p>Listings without a floor plan underperform listings that include one. The quality and completeness of the plans a seller provides is a meaningful signal to buyers about how the property has been prepared and how seriously the campaign is being run. This guide walks through each type of plan, what it shows, what it costs, and when it is worth providing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why plans matter to the sale</h2>

      <p>Serious buyers study floor plans more than any other marketing asset except photos. Plans tell buyers about flow, room sizes, aspect, storage, and renovation potential in a way that photos cannot. A buyer looking at a kitchen image cannot tell how far it is from the back deck, whether the living area is open plan or separated by a wall, or whether the main bedroom has room for a king bed and bedside tables. A good floor plan answers all of those questions at a glance.</p>

      <p>Floor plans also help buyers rule out properties that do not suit them, which is genuinely useful for the seller. Time spent walking a property that was never going to work is time the agent cannot spend with buyers who are serious. Clear plans tighten the buyer pool to those whose brief fits, which produces better inspections and better negotiation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The marketing-ready floor plan</h2>

      <p>A professionally drawn, scaled floor plan is the baseline for any Brisbane sale campaign. It is typically 2D, with room labels, dimensions in metres, a north arrow for orientation, and a total internal floor area. The floor plan is usually produced by the listing photographer during the main shoot, using a laser measure and a tablet, and finalised by their drafting team within a day or two.</p>

      <p>Costs in Brisbane sit broadly between $150 and $350 depending on property size and how many levels are included. For a standard three-bedroom single-storey home, $200 is normal. For a larger two-storey family home with multiple living areas, $300 to $350 is reasonable. This is among the cheapest and highest-value marketing assets a seller can provide. Leaving it out to save $200 on a campaign worth hundreds of thousands of dollars is a false economy.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a good floor plan shows</h2>

      <p>A strong marketing floor plan includes room dimensions in metres (not just square metreage), a north arrow so buyers can assess natural light and aspect, the location of key features (stairs, fireplaces, built-in robes, wardrobes, laundries, ensuites), door and window placements, and a total internal floor area broken down by level if the property has more than one storey. Outdoor spaces (covered decks, alfresco areas, verandahs) are usually shown with a different line weight or shading to distinguish them from internal space.</p>

      <p>A poor floor plan omits dimensions, leaves out the north arrow, mislabels rooms, or shows the property at a scale that is too small to read on a mobile phone. Buyers notice this. If the floor plan looks careless, buyers often assume the rest of the campaign is too.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The site plan</h2>

      <p>A site plan shows the property boundaries, the building footprint, and the position of the house on the lot. It is especially useful for buyers assessing yard space, aspect, privacy, and how the house sits relative to neighbouring properties. For larger blocks, corner blocks, battle-axe blocks, or properties where renovation or extension potential is a selling point, a site plan can meaningfully influence buyer interest.</p>

      <p>Site plans are usually derived from the Brisbane City Council's GIS (available via the council's planning scheme portal) or from the seller's conveyancing or title documents. A photographer can sometimes produce a simple site plan as part of the marketing package. For more detailed work, a draftsperson can produce a dimensioned site plan for $150 to $400.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Original building plans and architectural drawings</h2>

      <p>If the seller has the original approved building plans for the house, these can strengthen marketing significantly for renovated, architect-designed, or higher-value homes. Architectural drawings typically show electrical layouts, plumbing locations, structural elements, ceiling heights, and finishes schedules. For a buyer planning future renovations, these plans save thousands of dollars in early-stage design work and remove uncertainty about what is and is not practical.</p>

      <p>Sellers often have these plans stored in a filing cabinet or a digital folder and forget they exist. Before listing, it is worth checking for any original construction drawings, extension plans, or renovation drawings. If the plans exist, providing a PDF copy to serious buyers (not publishing them on the portal, but making them available on request) is a meaningful add to the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Council approval history</h2>

      <p>Buyers and their solicitors routinely search Brisbane City Council records to confirm that the physical structures on the property match the council's approval history. For older homes with extensions, decks, pergolas, or granny flats added over time, this search can reveal works that were never approved, which buyers treat as a risk to manage before they commit.</p>

      <p>Sellers who have completed renovations during their ownership should be ready to provide the approval documentation (building approvals, certificates of classification, Form 16s, Form 21s) to confirm everything is compliant. If any works were done without approval, sellers are better off identifying this before listing and deciding whether to pursue retrospective approval or disclose the issue openly. Buyers discovering it through a solicitor's search mid-contract is the worst possible outcome.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Zoning and planning overlays</h2>

      <p>The Brisbane City Council planning scheme (Brisbane City Plan 2014) identifies the zoning of every property, along with any applicable overlays. Overlays include flood risk, heritage or character protection, bushfire risk, landslide risk, traffic noise, and so on. Sophisticated buyers check these before making an offer, because overlays constrain what can be built or altered.</p>

      <p>Sellers of character homes, heritage-listed homes, or homes in flood overlays are well-served by pre-empting buyer concerns rather than waiting for them to surface mid-contract. This might mean including the council's overlay search in the marketing pack, engaging a town planner for a short advisory letter, or simply briefing the agent so they can answer questions confidently at open homes. Hiding the issue almost always backfires.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Strata and community titles plans (units and townhouses)</h2>

      <p>For units and townhouses, the survey plan showing the boundaries of the lot within the community titles scheme is essential. This plan distinguishes between what the unit owner actually owns (usually the internal space and any exclusive-use areas) and what is common property (usually hallways, gardens, pools, shared walls).</p>

      <p>Buyers routinely ask questions about balconies, courtyards, car parks, storage cages, and outdoor space. The survey plan answers most of these questions precisely. Sellers of apartments and townhouses should obtain a copy of the survey plan (usually available from the body corporate manager or the Titles Registry) and provide it alongside the standard floor plan. The body corporate disclosure statement (Form 11 or similar) that accompanies the contract usually attaches this plan already.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers often forget to include</h2>

      <p>Three areas are commonly left off floor plans: the loft, mezzanine, or attic if it is habitable; the garage or basement floor area; and significant outdoor covered areas. Each of these affects the total usable area a buyer perceives, which affects how they compare the property to other listings.</p>

      <p>A property with a 180 square metre internal floor plan but a 60 square metre covered alfresco and a 40 square metre garage has 280 square metres of functional space. Showing only the 180 undersells the property. The floor plan should show all three, appropriately distinguished, with the total clearly stated.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to include a 3D model or virtual tour alongside the 2D plan</h2>

      <p>A 2D floor plan is essential. A 3D model or virtual tour is optional and adds most value in two cases. The first is premium properties where buyers value spatial understanding and where the campaign budget supports it (typically above $2 million). The second is unconventional layouts, split-level homes, or properties with spatial features that 2D plans struggle to convey accurately.</p>

      <p>For most standard Brisbane family homes, a well-drawn 2D plan combined with strong photography and a quality video walkthrough is sufficient. A 3D model adds $500 to $1,500 to the campaign and is worthwhile where the property genuinely warrants it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do if the property was built or modified without plans</h2>

      <p>Some older Brisbane homes, particularly those built in the first half of the 20th century, do not have original plans. Others have been modified over time without formal drawings. In either case, engage a draftsperson to produce an as-built plan. Typical cost in Brisbane is $400 to $900 for a standard residential property, rising for larger or multi-storey homes.</p>

      <p>An as-built plan is a drawing of the property as it currently exists, produced by measuring the property on site. It can also support applications for retrospective council approval, if any works have been completed without approval. For any property where renovation potential is part of the pitch, an as-built plan is a worthwhile investment even if the marketing floor plan already exists.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>

      <p>Every marketing campaign should include a professionally drawn 2D floor plan. It is inexpensive, it resolves a lot of buyer uncertainty, and it is now expected by serious buyers in the Brisbane inner-east market. Leaving it out is a mistake.</p>

      <p>Higher-value or more complex properties benefit from a site plan, any available approval history, and, for units and townhouses, the survey plan from the community titles scheme. For renovated or character homes, original building plans or an as-built plan add real value. The principle is simple: every plan the seller provides resolves a question the buyer would otherwise have to answer themselves, and every answered question is one less reason for the buyer to hesitate.</p>

